Metal-organic framework (MOF) based composite materials have attracted significant research interest in the electrocatalytic field. In this study, a carbonized polypyrrole coated MOF composite electrocatalyst (C-MIL-101@PPy) is developed, which is a nitrogen-modified MOF-based carbon used as non-precious oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) electrocatalyst. Physical characterizations prove that the C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has high nitrogen doping (2.53 at.%) and effective graphite and pyridinium nitrogen doping (86.6%). When compared with commercial Pt/C, as-obtained C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst shows good ORR performance (∆E 1/2 = −22 mV) with good stability (87.8%) and methanol tolerance. All results indicate that MOF-based C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst is an effective and promising electrocatalyst for ORR. Graphcial abstract Unlabelled Image Keywords Metal-organic framework Nitrogen-doped carbon Oxygen reduction reaction Non-precious electrocatalyst 1 Introduction The state-of-the-art metal-organic framework (MOF), with a regular special morphology, adjustable apertures, and large specific surface area, has drawn wide research interest as a novel class of materials [1–4]. For electrocatalytic applications, the most classic way is using MOF as templates to obtain a series of nanocomposites. Many studies have shown that MOF can be used as template materials to prepare catalysts with many advantages [5,6]. It consists of a hollow and porous structure, which can avoid metal mass loss, and uniform pore size for improving the catalytic performance, while the regular structure is beneficial for the uniform distribution of the metal components and carbon. Currently, there are several reports that MOF can be used as a precursor or as a sacrificial template/precursor for preparation of various functional nanostructures, such as derived alloys, oxides, nitrides, carbides, and carbon materials, exhibiting excellent performance in electrocatalysis [7]. Carbonization of polymer materials, such as melamine resin, polyaniline, and chitosan, can result in a final carbon product with high nitrogen content and other good properties [8–10]. Polypyrrole (PPy) has good environmental stability, high electrical conductivity, and good redox property, making it one of the most promising and ideal polymer nitrogen modifiers to prepare carbon-based electrocatalytic materials. Recently, it has been proven that MOF as a skeleton/template is coated with high nitrogen content polymer materials and that, through the carbonization process, it can obtain good conductivity, stability, and oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) electrocatalytic performance [11–15]. Therefore, designing ways of incorporating active sites into the MOF-structure to make an advanced electrocatalyst would be an effective strategy to get improved catalytic activity toward ORR. In this work, a MOF of MIL-101 is coated with polypyrrole and then carbonized to obtain a target electrocatalyst of C-MIL-101@PPy, which is a nitrogen-modified MOF-based carbon, to be used as non-precious electrocatalyst for ORR. Subsequently, a series of tests show that as-prepared C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has a high nitrogen ratio (2.53 at.%). When compared with commercial Pt/C, the C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has good ORR catalytic activity, methanol tolerance, and stability (87.8%). This C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst would be an effective non-precious electrocatalyst for ORR in the future. 2 Experimental 2.1 Preparation of catalysts 2.1.1 Preparation of MIL-101(Fe) Firstly, iron nitrate hexahydrate (1.35 g, 5 mmol) and terephthalic acid (0.415 g, 2.5 mmol) were dissolved in N, N-dimethylformamide (DMF, 30 mL). Then, the solution was transferred to a 100 mL hydrothermal reaction vessel and reacted for 12 h at 110°C. The product was cooled to room temperature and was repeatedly washed with DMF and ethanol. Finally, the solid was dried in an oven at 60 °C for 12 h, which is MIL-101(Fe) (CAS:1189182-67-9). 2.1.2 Preparation of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst During the preparation, the C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst was obtained according to the following steps. Firstly, 50 mg of the MIL-101 (Fe) powder and 0.48 g of pyrrole monomer were dispersed in water (50 mL) by ultrasonic treatment for about 2 h. Subsequently, the solution was placed in an ice bath at 0 to 5 °C. Thereafter, an equal volume of mixed solution of 0.1 M HCl and 6 mmol FeCl3 was slowly dropped into the above solution and stirred for 24 h. The obtained carbon materials were dried in an oven at 60 °C for 12 h. Finally, the above product was treated via a carbonization process at 900 °C for 2 h. After carbonization, the resultant solid was washed repeatedly with 0.1 M HCl. The final sample was dried in a vacuum oven at 60 °C for 4 h and is named as C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst. 2.2 Structural characterizations The structure of catalysts was characterized by the following instruments, such as Raman, X-ray diffraction (XRD), Scanning electron microscopy (SEM), Transmission electronmicroscopy (TEM), and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS). Instrument types, sample pretreatment methods, and other details are all the same as in our previous study [16]. 2.3 Electrochemical tests The electrocatalytic performance was measured using the electrochemical workstation (PGSTAT 128 N Autolab, Switzerland) which used a standard three-electrode system, consisting of a reference electrode (Ag/AgCl), a counter electrode (graphite electrode), and a rotating disk electrode. The working electrode was prepared as follows. The catalyst was dispersed into a 5 mg mL−1 Nafion/ethanol solution. Subsequently, 8 μL was pipetted into the micro-sampler and added to the rotating disk electrode to evaporate the ethanol in the air. Typically, the loading is 0.2 mg cm−2. It should be noted that the catalyst was activated under N2 or O2 saturation conditions prior to each testing. 3 Results and discussion MOF-based composite materials have attracted significant research interest in the electrocatalysis field. However, the direct carbonization of MOF is not ideal in ORR performance due to limited catalysis active sites. Thus, most MOF materials, such as MIL-101, require introducing other components to increase active sites. Consequently, carbonization of polypyrrole-coated MIL-101 is a beneficial strategy for obtaining an effective ORR electrocatalyst. As shown in Fig. 1 , C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst, which is a nitrogen-modified MOF-based carbon, is prepared as non-precious ORR electrocatalyst. Firstly, the MOF of MIL-101 (Fe), used as the carbon skeleton template, was successfully prepared by the hydrothermal reaction method. Afterwards, MIL-101 (Fe) was covered with nitrogen-rich polypyrrole. Subsequently, the received product was carbonized at 900 °C. Finally, the nitrogen-modified MOF-based electrocatalyst (C-MIL-101@PPy) was obtained. Cyclic voltammetry (CV) of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst was performed in a N2 or O2 saturated 0.1 M KOH (Supporting Information, Fig. S1a). No redox features of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst can be observed in N2 condition. By contrast, there is a significant onset potential at −0.01 V under O2 saturation during reverse scanning, indicating that C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has ORR catalytic activity under O2 condition. To determine the ORR electrocatalytic activity of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst, a linear sweep voltammetry (LSV) was performed in 0.1 M KOH under O2 saturated condition at a rotation rate of 1600 rpm. Clearly, as illustrated in Fig. 2(a), compared to the half-wave potential (E 1/2) of commercial Pt/C (0.850 V), E 1/2 of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst (0.828 V) is slightly negatively shifted at approximately 22 mV (vs. RHE). It indicates that C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst is almost closer to the ORR catalytic performance of commercial Pt/C. Further, the E 1/2 value of ORR on C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst is much more positive than C-MIL-101 (no PPy coating reference), indicating that the introduction of polypyrrole in MIL-101 after carbonization can significantly favor the ORR. Generally, onset potential is defined as an indicator required for generating an ORR current, which is also an important criterion to evaluate the ORR catalyst activity [17,18]. The onset potential of C-MIL-101@PPy and C-MIL-101 electrocatalyst is 0.959 and 0.803 V, respectively. Obviously, C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst displays a more positive onset potential than C-MIL-101 and is closer to that of commercial Pt/C (1.003 V), which also indicates the good ORR performance of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst. As is known to all, small molecular compounds, such as methanol, can pass through the proton exchange membrane to reach the cathode in the actual use of the fuel cells. Therefore, methanol tolerance is also an important parameter for evaluating the performance of a catalyst. As shown in the insertion diagram of Fig. 2(a), the methanol tolerance of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst was characterized by polarization curves in 0.1 M KOH in the presence/absence of 0.5 M CH3OH. Obviously, the E 1/2 value of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst is quite close before and after (0.836 and 0.834 V, respectively) the introduction of the CH3OH in 0.1 M KOH solution. This means that C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has a high tolerance to methanol. However, commercial Pt/C has a significant negative shift in E 1/2 compared with absence of methanol and exhibits a big methanol oxidation current peak at about 0.864 V. (Supporting Information, Fig. S1b). Stability is another critical performance metric to assess catalytic performance [19]. To get the stability information of the catalyst, 30,000 s chronoamperometry (CA) test and accelerated durability test (ADT) of 1000 cycling were performed (Fig. 2(b)). As the test time increases, the relative current of the C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst and commercial Pt/C gradually decrease in chronoamperometry curves, which can be ascribed to the fact that catalysis active sites are occupied by reaction intermediate irreversible. Obviously, after the 30,000 s test, the C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has better current retention (87.8%), and commercial Pt/C only maintains 69.9% at the constant potential of 0.664 V. The 1000 cycling test is also consistent with the above results as shown in the Fig. 2(b) inserted. The onset potential of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst before and after the 1000 cycling is nearly the same. Further, the E 1/2 value of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst also almost remains the same (∆E 1/2 = 4 mV). However, after the 1000 cycling test, the onset potential of the commercial Pt/C negative shifted, and the E 1/2 is attenuated by 23 mV (∆E 1/2) (Supporting Information, Fig. S1c). All these results indicate that the C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has better stability than commercial Pt/C. The above tests indicate that, as-obtained C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has better ORR activity with good stability and methanol tolerance compared with commercial Pt/C, proving that the MOF-based materials are promising as ORR electrocatalysts. Moreover, we have compared the ORR electrocatalytic properties of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst with other N-doped carbon materials (Supporting Information, Table S1). As the structure of the catalyst determines catalytic properties, a series of physical characterizations were performed on C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst. To observe the effects of heat treatment, the structure and morphology of C-MIL-101 and C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst are observed in SEM images (Supporting Information, Fig. S2a and Fig. S2b). Before coating with polypyrrole, MIL-101 has a regular octahedral structure, which is in good agreement with literature [20,21]. After coating with polypyrrole and undergoing the carbonization process, C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst no longer has an obvious octahedron shape and becomes a carbon material with the common surface characteristics of carbon. However, as shown in the TEM image in Fig. 3 , C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has an obvious pore structure (marked by the red circles). Additionally, the insert in the right upper corner Fig. 3 is the HRTEM image. Obviously, C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has a graphitization characteristic, and the observed lattice fringe spacing of (002) lattice of carbon is 0.345 nm. Furthermore, it is confirmed that the C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has a typical face-centered cubic (fcc) polycrystalline structure through the selected area electron diffraction (SAED) pattern (Supporting Information, Fig. S2c). In Fig. 4(a), the XRD of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst shows significant peaks at 26.7° and 42.7°, which corresponds to the (002) crystal plane of carbon [22]. Further, the peaks at 29.3° and 35.5° correspond to the (220) and (311) crystal planes of Fe2.95O4 (PDF#86-1347), respectively. This indicates that some of the Fe elements in C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst are not completely removed during the etching process, which may be covered with the formed MOF-deviated carbon materials still existing in the C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst matrix. The degree of graphitization can be confirmed by the characterization of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst by Raman spectroscopy. In the inserted Raman spectroscopy of Fig. 4(a), the D peak represents the defect structure of the carbon materials, and the G peak represents the sp 2 hybridized graphitized carbon structure [23]. For C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst, obvious pair characteristic peaks are found at around 1345 cm−1 and 1595 cm−1 for D (disordered carbon) and G bands (sp2 hybridized graphitic carbon), respectively. C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has typical carbon structural defects which would generate active sites and enhance the ORR activity, while the intensity ratio (I D/I G) of the D peak (1345 cm−1) to the G peak (1595 cm−1) is 0.96. The G band intensity of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst is stronger than the D band, demonstrating that C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has a relatively high degree of graphitization, which would favor the stability of the structure. XPS was performed on C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst to analyze its element. The results indicate that C, N, and O are present on the surface of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst (Supporting Information, Fig. S3). In Fig. 4(b), the fitting analysis of the C 1 s peak mainly includes the following four bonding types: CC (284.8 eV), CN (285.6 eV), CN (286.8 eV), and OCO (289.3 eV) [24]. These results further confirm the polypyrrole coated on C-MIL-101 which results in nitrogen existence on carbon of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst. Meanwhile, in the fitting analysis of Fig. 4(c), it can be found that the C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst contains mainly four peak shapes of graphite nitrogen (400.9 eV), pyridine nitrogen (398.4 eV), pyrrole nitrogen (400.3 eV), and oxidized nitrogen (404.0 eV), in which nitrogen doping is 2.53 at.% and graphite nitrogen and pyridine nitrogen account for86.6%. It indicates that the nitrogen doping type is graphite nitrogen and pyridine nitrogen from the coated polypyrrole after carbonization [25]. According to the literature [26], pyridine nitrogen has a key influence on the initial potential of the ORR, while graphite nitrogen has a great influence on the limiting current density of the ORR. More importantly, pyridine nitrogen species contribute to the ORR reaction process from 2e− to 4e−, which would be conductive to improving the ORR performance of C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst. Above all, C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst exhibits good electrocatalysis performance toward ORR. However, there is no in-depth exhaustive study on optimizing the composite conditions of polypyrrole and MOF for obtaining optimal ORR materials at present. Further work for obtaining the best C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst and its application in fuel cells or Zinc-Air battery is still ongoing. 4 Conclusion In this study, C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst, a nitrogen-modified MOF-based carbon material used as a non-precious ORR electrocatalyst, is developed by carbonization of polypyrrole coated MIL-101 composite. The polypyrrole makes the final C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst having higher nitrogen doping (2.53 at.%) and a more effective nitrogen doping type (86.6%). The results demonstrate that as-prepared C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has better ORR electrocatalytic activity, stability, and methanol tolerance than commercial Pt/C. Developing MOF-based materials provide some new ideas for the development of advanced ORR electrocatalysts. coredata.dc:description: Metal-organic framework (MOF) based composite materials have attracted significant research interest in the electrocatalytic field. In this study, a carbonized polypyrrole coated MOF composite electrocatalyst (C-MIL-101@PPy) is developed, which is a nitrogen-modified MOF-based carbon used as non-precious oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) electrocatalyst. Physical characterizations prove that the C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst has high nitrogen doping (2.53 at.%) and effective graphite and pyridinium nitrogen doping (86.6%). When compared with commercial Pt/C, as-obtained C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst shows good ORR performance (∆E 1/2 = −22 mV) with good stability (87.8%) and methanol tolerance. All results indicate that MOF-based C-MIL-101@PPy electrocatalyst is an effective and promising electrocatalyst for ORR.
coredata.dc:title: Nitrogen-modified metal-organic framework-based carbon: An effective non-precious electrocatalyst for oxygen reduction reaction
